WEBVTT

00:00:00.960 --> 00:00:02.880
All right, great, thanks for coming to our talk today.

00:00:02.880 --> 00:00:04.640
We're gonna talk about self-sufficient deployment

00:00:04.640 --> 00:00:07.280
and how you can use paired programming to have fun.

00:00:08.120 --> 00:00:09.920
Okay, I know we just had a good lunch.

00:00:09.920 --> 00:00:10.880
We'll have a slow start.

00:00:10.880 --> 00:00:12.760
Let's start with our imagination a little bit.

00:00:12.760 --> 00:00:15.240
All right, so you hear the crunch of the gravel

00:00:15.240 --> 00:00:16.799
as you pull into a makeshift lot

00:00:16.799 --> 00:00:18.900
in the foothills of Appalachian Mountains.

00:00:20.000 --> 00:00:21.540
You look out and you see the billboard.

00:00:21.540 --> 00:00:23.620
There it is, the course map.

00:00:23.620 --> 00:00:26.799
25 obstacles over 12 miles.

00:00:26.799 --> 00:00:30.440
Seven of those obstacles are mystery obstacles.

00:00:30.440 --> 00:00:31.879
And the course is gonna take place

00:00:31.879 --> 00:00:34.900
over 1,600 feet of elevation change.

00:00:34.900 --> 00:00:36.480
This is exactly where Kris and I,

00:00:36.480 --> 00:00:37.939
two data scientists from Nissan,

00:00:37.939 --> 00:00:40.919
found ourselves one crisp fall morning.

00:00:40.919 --> 00:00:44.360
We came ready to take on an intense obstacle course race,

00:00:44.360 --> 00:00:47.599
but what we actually got was a real-world lesson

00:00:47.599 --> 00:00:49.040
in paired programming.

00:00:50.400 --> 00:00:51.520
How?

00:00:51.520 --> 00:00:53.520
There's actually a lot more in common than you think.

00:00:53.520 --> 00:00:55.759
So the 25 obstacles over 12 miles

00:00:55.759 --> 00:00:57.439
took a lot of preparation.

00:00:57.439 --> 00:01:00.000
We call this stability in our data science projects.

00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:02.480
The mystery obstacles, arguably more important,

00:01:02.480 --> 00:01:04.519
it's that adaptability to those problems

00:01:04.519 --> 00:01:06.760
or obstacles that come up.

00:01:06.760 --> 00:01:09.239
The elevation change, that's the backdrop

00:01:09.239 --> 00:01:11.500
of every race, of every problem.

00:01:11.500 --> 00:01:12.559
It's the difficulty,

00:01:12.559 --> 00:01:15.199
and you need to come with the right mindset.

00:01:15.199 --> 00:01:17.879
So sometimes that's just getting started,

00:01:17.879 --> 00:01:19.639
like we did with our wristbands.

00:01:19.639 --> 00:01:21.160
So at the end of the day,

00:01:21.160 --> 00:01:23.639
we found that projects at work,

00:01:23.639 --> 00:01:26.000
as well as obstacle course races outside of work,

00:01:26.000 --> 00:01:28.639
we worked better together than alone.

00:01:28.639 --> 00:01:29.639
I'm gonna hand it over to Kris

00:01:29.639 --> 00:01:31.699
to talk about our Spartan races at work.

00:01:33.040 --> 00:01:35.320
So I'm gonna tell you about a case study

00:01:35.320 --> 00:01:37.199
that we did at work at Nissan.

00:01:37.199 --> 00:01:38.800
But the details of the case study aren't important.

00:01:38.800 --> 00:01:39.879
We're just using it to show you

00:01:39.879 --> 00:01:41.959
that we actually really did use paired programming

00:01:41.959 --> 00:01:43.720
in a real project.

00:01:43.720 --> 00:01:46.160
So like Kristin said, we work at Nissan,

00:01:46.160 --> 00:01:47.839
and we both work in supply chain.

00:01:47.839 --> 00:01:49.639
So sometimes we have to bring in parts,

00:01:49.639 --> 00:01:52.160
we have to bring in shipping containers,

00:01:52.160 --> 00:01:54.000
and we were approached with a problem

00:01:54.000 --> 00:01:58.800
of predicting a thing called monthly container fill ratio.

00:01:58.800 --> 00:02:00.760
And container fill ratio is just the KPI

00:02:00.760 --> 00:02:02.239
we use in supply chain,

00:02:02.239 --> 00:02:04.599
and it's the simple ratio of the space

00:02:04.599 --> 00:02:07.040
the package takes up divided by the full space

00:02:07.040 --> 00:02:07.879
in the container.

00:02:09.919 --> 00:02:12.639
So we needed to deploy this self-sufficiently.

00:02:12.639 --> 00:02:14.839
We are a business team of data scientists.

00:02:14.839 --> 00:02:15.919
We are not an IS team.

00:02:15.919 --> 00:02:17.960
We were not gonna hand this off to an IS team.

00:02:17.960 --> 00:02:19.720
We're deploying this solution

00:02:19.720 --> 00:02:21.800
to some other people in supply chain,

00:02:22.440 --> 00:02:24.520
and we needed to be able to do that self-sufficiently.

00:02:24.520 --> 00:02:27.119
If you've ever tried to deploy a project self-sufficiently,

00:02:27.119 --> 00:02:28.240
you may have encountered,

00:02:28.240 --> 00:02:31.479
there are sort of these two competing project components

00:02:31.479 --> 00:02:33.199
that you have to figure out.

00:02:33.199 --> 00:02:34.320
There's reactivity.

00:02:34.320 --> 00:02:35.960
You need to be able to respond quickly enough

00:02:35.960 --> 00:02:40.960
to solve the problem before the problem becomes obsolete.

00:02:41.399 --> 00:02:43.199
And you also need to have stability.

00:02:43.199 --> 00:02:44.839
So you kind of need to go slow enough

00:02:44.839 --> 00:02:47.600
so that when you deploy it, it can last over time.

00:02:48.919 --> 00:02:50.880
Let's take a look at this first problem.

00:02:50.880 --> 00:02:53.039
Solutions need to be reactive.

00:02:53.039 --> 00:02:55.360
So when we're developing projects,

00:02:55.360 --> 00:02:58.199
we need to not develop like this.

00:02:58.199 --> 00:03:00.440
We need to make sure that we have,

00:03:00.440 --> 00:03:02.320
we don't wanna wait until the very end

00:03:02.320 --> 00:03:04.199
to have a working solution.

00:03:04.199 --> 00:03:06.199
We wanna make sure that we're actually having

00:03:06.199 --> 00:03:08.440
little tiny working solutions as we go.

00:03:08.440 --> 00:03:11.080
I think everybody agrees this is the right way to develop.

00:03:11.080 --> 00:03:13.779
I'm gonna argue this is also a deployment type.

00:03:20.880 --> 00:03:24.039
So, there we go.

00:03:24.039 --> 00:03:26.600
So each part of this deployment,

00:03:26.600 --> 00:03:29.360
we wanna have something working from the beginning, right?

00:03:29.360 --> 00:03:31.800
So we have a skateboard and it can actually work.

00:03:31.800 --> 00:03:33.520
It may not be your full project.

00:03:33.520 --> 00:03:35.399
You're gonna add a component to it

00:03:35.399 --> 00:03:36.779
and then it's gonna be working

00:03:36.779 --> 00:03:39.479
and you're gonna keep going like that.

00:03:39.479 --> 00:03:40.820
In our case study, right,

00:03:40.820 --> 00:03:42.320
that simple machine learning problem

00:03:42.320 --> 00:03:44.220
that we were gonna predict,

00:03:44.220 --> 00:03:46.479
this may have looked like in the first stage

00:03:46.479 --> 00:03:48.559
we have developed a few models

00:03:48.559 --> 00:03:50.119
and then we go back to the business and say,

00:03:50.160 --> 00:03:52.800
hey, do you want the model that's most interpretable

00:03:52.800 --> 00:03:55.000
or the model that is the most accurate?

00:03:55.000 --> 00:03:57.119
And then we can go forward and now we know that piece

00:03:57.119 --> 00:03:59.199
and we can add some handlebars to it

00:03:59.199 --> 00:04:01.520
and go forward with the project.

00:04:01.520 --> 00:04:02.860
So you may be starting to see

00:04:02.860 --> 00:04:05.399
how working with a second programmer

00:04:05.399 --> 00:04:07.240
is starting to benefit your projects.

00:04:08.440 --> 00:04:10.440
The second problem that deployments often have

00:04:10.440 --> 00:04:13.440
is that solutions need to be stable over time.

00:04:13.440 --> 00:04:16.000
So I'm currently teaching my daughter how to ride a bike.

00:04:16.000 --> 00:04:17.540
If you've ever done this,

00:04:17.579 --> 00:04:20.140
you understand the importance of support

00:04:20.140 --> 00:04:21.559
to develop that stability.

00:04:22.940 --> 00:04:24.380
At the end of the process of teaching her

00:04:24.380 --> 00:04:25.220
how to ride a bike,

00:04:25.220 --> 00:04:27.260
the goal is that she can ride by herself, right?

00:04:27.260 --> 00:04:28.799
I know how to ride a bike, she can ride a bike,

00:04:28.799 --> 00:04:30.540
either one of us can ride the bike.

00:04:32.059 --> 00:04:34.579
Stability requires sufficient support

00:04:35.980 --> 00:04:38.459
or else everyone is angry crying.

00:04:38.459 --> 00:04:40.320
She was very happy she could be in my presentation

00:04:40.320 --> 00:04:41.660
and she did not mind me sharing

00:04:41.660 --> 00:04:43.619
this unflattering photo of her.

00:04:45.079 --> 00:04:47.200
This is true not only in learning to ride a bike,

00:04:47.880 --> 00:04:49.720
it's also true in data science projects, right?

00:04:49.720 --> 00:04:52.040
So for our project to be deployed,

00:04:52.040 --> 00:04:56.359
this little simple CFR, we wanna predict something,

00:04:56.359 --> 00:04:58.880
we needed to be able to walk away from it

00:04:58.880 --> 00:05:02.799
and go on vacation or come to Posit Conf and speak to you.

00:05:02.799 --> 00:05:05.079
And so we needed stability in that deployment

00:05:05.079 --> 00:05:06.320
so that we could do that.

00:05:07.799 --> 00:05:09.359
I'm gonna take a minute and help you

00:05:09.359 --> 00:05:11.000
see the interaction of these two.

00:05:11.000 --> 00:05:13.760
You have to hold them in tension, right?

00:05:13.760 --> 00:05:16.839
You can't go quickly and go slowly at the same time.

00:05:17.540 --> 00:05:18.380
Across the bottom here,

00:05:18.380 --> 00:05:19.739
we have different deployment types,

00:05:19.739 --> 00:05:21.359
the simplest being on the left,

00:05:21.359 --> 00:05:23.959
the most complex deployment type being on the right.

00:05:23.959 --> 00:05:26.160
And we are, again, a business team,

00:05:26.160 --> 00:05:27.760
so we are only in control

00:05:27.760 --> 00:05:29.160
of sort of these three on the left here.

00:05:29.160 --> 00:05:31.660
These are self-sufficient deployment types.

00:05:31.660 --> 00:05:33.519
So a manual ad hoc analysis,

00:05:33.519 --> 00:05:35.640
I know you may be arguing that's not really deployment,

00:05:35.640 --> 00:05:37.200
but remember we're doing these quick iterations,

00:05:37.200 --> 00:05:40.040
so we're counting that as a deployment type.

00:05:40.040 --> 00:05:42.100
A local deployment is where you have it on your laptop,

00:05:42.100 --> 00:05:43.359
maybe the business tells me,

00:05:43.399 --> 00:05:45.040
hey, can you go get those predictions again?

00:05:45.040 --> 00:05:46.760
And I'm like, sure, tick, tick, tick, tick,

00:05:46.760 --> 00:05:49.320
and I email them back the predictions.

00:05:49.320 --> 00:05:52.160
And then the third level here is a team server deployment.

00:05:52.160 --> 00:05:53.859
That's where maybe I'm sending predictions

00:05:53.859 --> 00:05:55.839
up to a database or to a server,

00:05:55.839 --> 00:05:57.720
and the end users can actually go access that

00:05:57.720 --> 00:05:59.679
without having to come through me.

00:05:59.679 --> 00:06:02.640
So what does reactivity look like

00:06:02.640 --> 00:06:04.859
on these different deployment types?

00:06:04.859 --> 00:06:06.420
It's gonna start out really high, right?

00:06:06.420 --> 00:06:07.920
You're gonna be able to respond really quickly

00:06:07.920 --> 00:06:09.959
to changes that the business needs.

00:06:09.959 --> 00:06:11.359
So side note, as it turns out,

00:06:11.399 --> 00:06:13.600
that CFR calculation, that really simple one,

00:06:13.600 --> 00:06:16.480
they actually changed it on us once we had it deployed,

00:06:16.480 --> 00:06:19.000
and so we had to go back and quickly update that,

00:06:19.000 --> 00:06:20.200
and we were able to do that

00:06:20.200 --> 00:06:22.980
because we had a self-sufficient deployment.

00:06:22.980 --> 00:06:24.359
So reactivity's gonna start really high,

00:06:24.359 --> 00:06:26.459
it's gonna decrease as you go to the right.

00:06:26.459 --> 00:06:29.279
But support, stability is gonna do just the opposite, right?

00:06:29.279 --> 00:06:30.200
It's gonna start out really low,

00:06:30.200 --> 00:06:31.799
you're probably the only one working on the project,

00:06:31.799 --> 00:06:33.959
but as you get to more complex deployments,

00:06:33.959 --> 00:06:37.279
you need to make sure that you have more people involved.

00:06:37.279 --> 00:06:40.440
So the goal is you wanna retain maximum reactivity

00:06:40.440 --> 00:06:43.320
with sufficient support to ensure stability.

00:06:43.320 --> 00:06:44.799
So back to our case study, right?

00:06:44.799 --> 00:06:46.399
The simple machine learning prediction.

00:06:46.399 --> 00:06:47.920
We started here, it was pretty easy

00:06:47.920 --> 00:06:49.119
to get to this local deployment.

00:06:49.119 --> 00:06:50.040
I had it on my laptop,

00:06:50.040 --> 00:06:51.440
I could email back and forth with people,

00:06:51.440 --> 00:06:54.320
but I needed to move it up to a team server deployment

00:06:54.320 --> 00:06:56.239
so I could come speak to you.

00:06:56.239 --> 00:06:57.640
But I couldn't do that by myself.

00:06:57.640 --> 00:07:01.000
I physically can't have the support that I need

00:07:01.000 --> 00:07:03.880
to have stability if it's just me.

00:07:03.880 --> 00:07:05.440
Thankfully, we had just read an article

00:07:05.440 --> 00:07:07.079
about pair programming,

00:07:07.079 --> 00:07:11.040
and it gave us the tools we needed to sell our leaders

00:07:11.040 --> 00:07:13.679
on using pair programming to solve this problem.

00:07:13.679 --> 00:07:14.760
I'm gonna hand it back to Kristen now

00:07:14.760 --> 00:07:16.359
to tell you about that article.

00:07:17.799 --> 00:07:19.600
Great, so we now have a product

00:07:19.600 --> 00:07:21.519
that's both reactive and stable,

00:07:21.519 --> 00:07:25.239
but to get there, we need to justify to our leadership

00:07:25.239 --> 00:07:27.559
two resources on one project.

00:07:27.559 --> 00:07:29.040
So we started doing some research,

00:07:29.040 --> 00:07:30.359
and this review article is one

00:07:30.359 --> 00:07:32.119
that we're gonna quote today came up,

00:07:32.119 --> 00:07:34.640
and it really helped us strengthen our argument.

00:07:35.519 --> 00:07:37.480
The first thing is 15% more time

00:07:37.480 --> 00:07:40.959
is gonna save you 15% less in defects.

00:07:40.959 --> 00:07:44.119
So we're not Geico, but the concept applies.

00:07:44.119 --> 00:07:48.559
15% more time and defects are very different.

00:07:48.559 --> 00:07:50.600
That's not only defects in your code and your project,

00:07:50.600 --> 00:07:52.440
but that's any downstream process

00:07:52.440 --> 00:07:54.200
that you have hooked up to the product

00:07:54.200 --> 00:07:55.399
that you delivered.

00:07:55.399 --> 00:07:58.519
So that's really valuable.

00:07:58.519 --> 00:08:00.640
The second thing is, is it fun?

00:08:00.640 --> 00:08:03.720
Yeah, after programmers tried pair programming,

00:08:03.720 --> 00:08:05.200
90% preferred it.

00:08:06.119 --> 00:08:07.440
Does it work?

00:08:07.440 --> 00:08:11.119
Solo developers only passed 75% of test cases.

00:08:11.119 --> 00:08:13.799
Paired developers passed about 90.

00:08:13.799 --> 00:08:15.480
So this was a really strong argument,

00:08:15.480 --> 00:08:17.279
to come in and say, yep, we're gonna have

00:08:17.279 --> 00:08:19.119
a more reliable solution to the business

00:08:19.119 --> 00:08:20.920
and create that faith in our products.

00:08:20.920 --> 00:08:22.640
We're gonna have fun while we do it,

00:08:22.640 --> 00:08:25.320
and we're gonna get better and more creative solutions.

00:08:25.320 --> 00:08:29.040
Okay, so we were convinced, and we're ready to tackle this.

00:08:29.040 --> 00:08:31.200
So how do we do pair programming?

00:08:31.200 --> 00:08:33.840
Before we get into strategies for pair programming,

00:08:33.840 --> 00:08:35.000
let's talk about what it's not,

00:08:35.000 --> 00:08:37.320
in case you've heard this term before.

00:08:37.320 --> 00:08:38.520
So the first thing is, pair programming

00:08:38.520 --> 00:08:40.119
is not backseat driving.

00:08:41.000 --> 00:08:43.679
The second thing is, it's not 24-7 grind.

00:08:43.679 --> 00:08:45.039
This isn't sitting next to each other,

00:08:45.039 --> 00:08:47.679
looking at the screen for eight hours a day.

00:08:47.679 --> 00:08:50.440
It's also not keyboard hogging.

00:08:50.440 --> 00:08:54.640
So it's sharing the ideas, sharing the coding, all of it.

00:08:54.640 --> 00:08:57.599
And then, lastly, it's not nap time.

00:08:57.599 --> 00:08:59.880
So this is coming to the problem,

00:08:59.880 --> 00:09:02.960
engaged with that mindset, ready to take on the difficulty.

00:09:02.960 --> 00:09:04.799
So now that you know what it's not,

00:09:04.799 --> 00:09:05.719
I'm gonna hand it back to Chris

00:09:05.719 --> 00:09:06.880
to talk about some of the strategies

00:09:06.880 --> 00:09:09.840
that you can use to use pair programming in your projects.

00:09:10.799 --> 00:09:13.200
So there are a lot of approaches to pair programming.

00:09:13.200 --> 00:09:15.119
The most common one is called driver navigator.

00:09:15.119 --> 00:09:16.280
It is just what it sounds like.

00:09:16.280 --> 00:09:17.880
One person is driving at the keyboard.

00:09:17.880 --> 00:09:19.320
The other person is helping navigate,

00:09:19.320 --> 00:09:22.200
looking for speed bumps, left turns ahead,

00:09:22.200 --> 00:09:23.599
helping you get through that.

00:09:24.559 --> 00:09:26.000
A second approach is called ping pong.

00:09:26.000 --> 00:09:28.599
This is more common in software engineering,

00:09:28.599 --> 00:09:30.359
but I think it's useful for data science as well,

00:09:30.359 --> 00:09:32.559
especially if you have a lot of functions in your code.

00:09:32.559 --> 00:09:35.880
Basically, one person starts with the idea for the function,

00:09:35.880 --> 00:09:38.080
the second person will implement the code for that function,

00:09:38.080 --> 00:09:39.440
and then the first person will go back

00:09:39.440 --> 00:09:41.119
and refactor that function,

00:09:41.119 --> 00:09:43.840
and then the next time they switch roles.

00:09:43.840 --> 00:09:45.400
I wanna introduce a really important term here

00:09:45.400 --> 00:09:46.960
called refactoring.

00:09:46.960 --> 00:09:48.679
This is a process I've sort of always done,

00:09:48.679 --> 00:09:51.400
but I didn't actually know it had a name for it.

00:09:51.400 --> 00:09:53.640
It's the process of making the code more readable,

00:09:53.640 --> 00:09:55.119
maintainable, and efficient.

00:09:55.119 --> 00:09:56.400
So you've probably done it too,

00:09:56.400 --> 00:09:57.760
but it's really important to call out here

00:09:57.760 --> 00:10:00.200
because it's a hugely critical component

00:10:00.200 --> 00:10:01.320
of pair programming.

00:10:02.400 --> 00:10:05.559
A third approach is called unstructured synchronous.

00:10:05.559 --> 00:10:06.840
Unstructured here does not mean

00:10:06.840 --> 00:10:08.239
like just do whatever you feel like,

00:10:08.239 --> 00:10:10.719
and like there's no plan.

00:10:10.719 --> 00:10:12.400
It just means that it's not so formal.

00:10:12.400 --> 00:10:15.500
You don't have to like your turn, my turn, your turn.

00:10:15.500 --> 00:10:17.520
You can lean into your strengths and your interests

00:10:17.520 --> 00:10:18.359
a little bit more.

00:10:18.359 --> 00:10:21.239
Synchronous means you're sharing time and space.

00:10:21.239 --> 00:10:25.200
So a program, a problem being solved with this approach

00:10:25.200 --> 00:10:27.080
might look something like this,

00:10:27.080 --> 00:10:29.280
where you are working on different project components

00:10:29.280 --> 00:10:31.000
together, you're sharing time and space,

00:10:31.000 --> 00:10:33.280
and you are doing that refactoring together.

00:10:34.359 --> 00:10:36.640
A fourth approach is called unstructured asynchronous.

00:10:36.640 --> 00:10:38.039
So same meaning of unstructured,

00:10:38.039 --> 00:10:39.200
asynchronous here just meaning

00:10:39.200 --> 00:10:41.919
you're not sharing time and space.

00:10:41.919 --> 00:10:44.520
And I affectionately call this parallel programming

00:10:44.520 --> 00:10:47.799
because I am a dad and I have to have my dad jokes.

00:10:49.119 --> 00:10:51.979
So this approach could look like this,

00:10:51.979 --> 00:10:53.000
where you have one person doing

00:10:53.000 --> 00:10:54.440
maybe these two project components,

00:10:54.440 --> 00:10:56.500
another person doing this project component,

00:10:56.500 --> 00:10:58.179
and maybe they're doing them at the same time,

00:10:58.179 --> 00:10:59.940
but they are not doing them together.

00:10:59.940 --> 00:11:01.659
They're not sharing time and space.

00:11:01.659 --> 00:11:03.539
And I know you think that I'm totally cheating now

00:11:03.539 --> 00:11:05.440
because now I'm not even talking about pair programming.

00:11:05.440 --> 00:11:07.580
You're like, that's just regular programming,

00:11:07.580 --> 00:11:09.500
except we're not done with the project, right?

00:11:09.500 --> 00:11:13.380
Because there's this really important step of refactoring.

00:11:13.380 --> 00:11:16.659
And if you will pause and go back and refactor together,

00:11:16.659 --> 00:11:20.299
maybe even all switching who like takes the lead,

00:11:20.299 --> 00:11:23.020
you're gonna achieve the pairing that you need

00:11:23.020 --> 00:11:24.460
to make this successful.

00:11:24.460 --> 00:11:26.500
The goal at the end of whichever approach

00:11:26.500 --> 00:11:28.260
or approaches you choose is that

00:11:28.260 --> 00:11:29.780
everybody can ride the bike.

00:11:31.659 --> 00:11:33.580
So we're gonna go back to that case study.

00:11:33.580 --> 00:11:35.500
Remember that simple machine learning model

00:11:35.500 --> 00:11:38.000
we're trying to predict for Nissan.

00:11:38.000 --> 00:11:40.099
We used both of these approaches,

00:11:40.099 --> 00:11:42.580
driver navigator and unstructured asynchronous.

00:11:42.580 --> 00:11:45.880
We're gonna show you how we did that to solve this problem.

00:11:45.880 --> 00:11:48.979
If you came to this talk for the technical details,

00:11:48.979 --> 00:11:51.080
the raw code about how we did this,

00:11:51.080 --> 00:11:53.780
we have that in, you can access that in a QR code

00:11:53.780 --> 00:11:54.700
at the end of the presentation.

00:11:54.700 --> 00:11:56.500
That's not what I'm doing right now.

00:11:57.619 --> 00:11:59.820
I'm gonna give you a high level architecture

00:11:59.820 --> 00:12:01.099
of how we solved this problem

00:12:01.099 --> 00:12:02.539
to show you the tools we used

00:12:02.539 --> 00:12:04.219
and how we used pair programming.

00:12:04.219 --> 00:12:07.780
So we used tidy models to build the machine learning model

00:12:07.780 --> 00:12:08.619
in R.

00:12:08.619 --> 00:12:09.900
Tidy models, if you don't know,

00:12:09.900 --> 00:12:13.260
is a framework, a package built and maintained by Posit

00:12:13.260 --> 00:12:16.460
that helps you create machine learning models

00:12:16.460 --> 00:12:19.299
and then build all the workflows you need to deploy them.

00:12:20.419 --> 00:12:23.219
The most important piece of architecture that we had

00:12:23.580 --> 00:12:26.179
to deploy this self-sufficiently was Posit Connect.

00:12:26.179 --> 00:12:28.099
If you haven't heard enough about Posit Connect yet

00:12:28.099 --> 00:12:32.619
at conference, it is one of Posit's commercial offerings.

00:12:32.619 --> 00:12:36.659
We are so thankful that Nissan has a Posit Connect server

00:12:36.659 --> 00:12:38.099
that we pay for.

00:12:38.099 --> 00:12:40.700
And so this allows us to sort of,

00:12:40.700 --> 00:12:42.460
I think of it as a bulletin board, right?

00:12:42.460 --> 00:12:44.619
And I can make all my cool data science stuff

00:12:44.619 --> 00:12:46.460
and I can like pin it to my bulletin board

00:12:46.460 --> 00:12:49.500
and other people can walk by and like do stuff with it.

00:12:49.500 --> 00:12:51.619
And so we have a Posit Connect server.

00:12:52.619 --> 00:12:55.099
We use a package called vetiver,

00:12:55.099 --> 00:12:57.500
also a Posit maintained package

00:12:57.500 --> 00:13:00.419
that allows us to take that model from a laptop, right?

00:13:00.419 --> 00:13:01.979
And put it up on Posit Connect.

00:13:01.979 --> 00:13:05.140
It's like the push pin in the bulletin board.

00:13:05.140 --> 00:13:06.859
And it also created an API for us

00:13:06.859 --> 00:13:10.219
so we could interact with that model really nicely.

00:13:10.219 --> 00:13:11.900
Finally, we used Streamlet,

00:13:11.900 --> 00:13:16.900
which is a Python package for building web applications.

00:13:17.380 --> 00:13:19.059
It is not a Posit product,

00:13:19.059 --> 00:13:21.900
but it works really, really nicely with Posit products.

00:13:21.900 --> 00:13:24.059
And so we use that Streamlet app to call the API

00:13:24.059 --> 00:13:26.820
and display the predictions to the end user.

00:13:28.020 --> 00:13:31.340
So how did we do this with pair programming, right?

00:13:31.340 --> 00:13:34.099
So I took the lead on developing the model

00:13:34.099 --> 00:13:37.140
while Kristen was developing the UI in Streamlet.

00:13:37.140 --> 00:13:40.099
And so this is that unstructured asynchronous approach.

00:13:40.099 --> 00:13:41.900
We came back together and refactored

00:13:41.900 --> 00:13:43.659
each of those code sets together.

00:13:43.659 --> 00:13:46.099
And so we both knew what was going on at the end.

00:13:47.099 --> 00:13:49.340
We used the driver navigator approach

00:13:49.340 --> 00:13:52.419
for the Vetiver portion because it was new to us.

00:13:52.419 --> 00:13:54.460
We had gone to PositConf 2024

00:13:54.460 --> 00:13:56.619
and went to some really good workshops with Vetiver.

00:13:56.619 --> 00:13:57.820
So we knew what it could do,

00:13:57.820 --> 00:13:59.940
but we had never actually done it in the wild.

00:13:59.940 --> 00:14:01.619
So we felt a little more comfortable doing that

00:14:01.619 --> 00:14:04.739
like together, sharing brainpower together.

00:14:04.739 --> 00:14:08.179
So in the end, we were able to solve our problem at Nissan.

00:14:08.179 --> 00:14:10.659
We were able to successfully deploy

00:14:10.659 --> 00:14:13.979
this machine learning algorithm self-sufficiently

00:14:14.059 --> 00:14:15.340
through these tools,

00:14:15.340 --> 00:14:17.979
and we achieved the reactivity that we needed

00:14:17.979 --> 00:14:19.539
because we worked together,

00:14:19.539 --> 00:14:21.659
and we achieved the stability that we needed

00:14:21.659 --> 00:14:23.659
because of pair programming.

00:14:23.659 --> 00:14:24.940
So now that we have talked about

00:14:24.940 --> 00:14:28.099
how we solved our problem with pair programming,

00:14:28.099 --> 00:14:30.460
Kristen is gonna talk you through a few lessons learned

00:14:30.460 --> 00:14:33.900
so that you can solve a problem with pair programming.

00:14:36.460 --> 00:14:38.260
Right, so it worked really well for us.

00:14:38.260 --> 00:14:39.500
How does it work for you?

00:14:39.500 --> 00:14:41.979
So the biggest thing to take away is pairing is a mindset.

00:14:41.979 --> 00:14:42.820
It's not a technique.

00:14:42.820 --> 00:14:44.419
There is no recipe, there's no textbook

00:14:44.419 --> 00:14:45.900
that's gonna tell you exactly how to do it

00:14:45.900 --> 00:14:47.659
because everyone's different,

00:14:47.659 --> 00:14:49.140
and the dynamic between two people

00:14:49.140 --> 00:14:51.020
is gonna be different every time.

00:14:51.020 --> 00:14:52.340
Follow the vibe.

00:14:52.340 --> 00:14:53.739
What gets you traction?

00:14:53.739 --> 00:14:55.020
Roll with it.

00:14:55.020 --> 00:14:58.260
The next thing is if I could do every project

00:14:58.260 --> 00:15:00.299
with my work bestie, of course I would,

00:15:00.299 --> 00:15:02.580
but friction will find you no matter what,

00:15:02.580 --> 00:15:04.299
and that's not bad.

00:15:04.299 --> 00:15:06.820
We've heard in other talks that that is what helps.

00:15:06.820 --> 00:15:08.619
Creativity makes better solutions.

00:15:08.619 --> 00:15:09.859
So embrace it, roll with it.

00:15:09.859 --> 00:15:11.099
I mean, of course, be respectful,

00:15:11.099 --> 00:15:14.340
but it's a good thing.

00:15:14.340 --> 00:15:16.780
And finally, slow down to speed up.

00:15:16.780 --> 00:15:18.140
So you've heard a lot about refactoring.

00:15:18.140 --> 00:15:20.979
This is also like when you're working with your teammate

00:15:20.979 --> 00:15:22.140
and you're talking through problems,

00:15:22.140 --> 00:15:24.219
take that time so you both fully understand it

00:15:24.219 --> 00:15:26.739
and move forward with the progress.

00:15:26.739 --> 00:15:28.580
So the second is know your strength

00:15:28.580 --> 00:15:30.460
and adapt for your weaknesses.

00:15:30.460 --> 00:15:32.059
So for our particular project,

00:15:32.059 --> 00:15:33.539
our skills were very isolated,

00:15:33.539 --> 00:15:34.859
and in fact, Vetiver was outside

00:15:34.859 --> 00:15:37.020
both of our circles of knowledge.

00:15:37.020 --> 00:15:39.859
After the project, we were both experts on everything.

00:15:39.859 --> 00:15:42.539
So now you see where that reactivity, that stability,

00:15:42.539 --> 00:15:47.539
that paradox of delivering a solid project comes in.

00:15:48.020 --> 00:15:50.539
And then finally, the final lesson is create this checkpoint.

00:15:50.539 --> 00:15:51.780
So you've made this progress.

00:15:51.780 --> 00:15:53.179
How do you save it?

00:15:53.179 --> 00:15:55.179
And so refactoring is really important.

00:15:55.179 --> 00:15:57.460
This is your code-level checkpoint.

00:15:57.460 --> 00:15:59.020
Make sure that your code is good.

00:15:59.020 --> 00:16:00.859
Take out all the leaks so that you don't have

00:16:00.859 --> 00:16:03.299
that catastrophic damage way down the line.

00:16:03.299 --> 00:16:06.859
So let's take that code and let's expand it to our team,

00:16:06.859 --> 00:16:08.700
our pair programming team, right?

